Wasatch Estates is planning a residential development of single‐family homes on estate sized
lots and luxury residential cluster homes. The property has frontage to and will obtain access
from Dublin Road and Memorial Drive, which are under the jurisdiction of the City of Dublin,
Ohio. The development will likely occur over a period of time. It is anticipated that this
proposed development would create additional traffic that could possibly impact operations at
the adjacent intersections in the area. These intersections include the intersection of Dublin
Road and Memorial Drive, Dublin Road and Deer Run Drive N, and Memorial Drive and
Autumnwood Way / Deer Run Drive E. Deer Run Drive E and Deer Run Drive N will be private
This traffic impact study is being prepared for review by the City of Dublin. The communication
with the City of Dublin including the Memorandum of Understanding submitted to the City and
comments received are provided in Appendix A. The purpose of the study is to review the
existing roadway and traffic conditions adjacent to the project site and the likely impacts on the
adjacent intersections. This study first documents the current characteristics of the study area in
terms of land uses, roads, and traffic volumes. Next, the study forecasts the volumes and
distribution of the traffic generated due to the proposed residential development and analyzes
the impacts on the adjacent roadways. Although the proposed residential development is
planned to occur over time, only the analyses of the “opening day” and the “horizon year” (ten
years beyond the opening day) were performed, per the City’s requirements. Finally, the study
presents recommendations for site access and any related adjacent road and intersection
The site is located in the northeast corner of the intersection of Dublin Road (SR 745) and
Memorial Drive, City of Dublin, Ohio. A site location map is shown on Figure 1.
The area along Dublin Road and Memorial Drive is primarily residential. For the most part, the
Dublin Road (SR 745) is a north‐south roadway that runs along the west edge of the proposed
Deer Run development. Dublin Road is a two‐lane roadway with a speed limit of 45 mph. At the
intersection with Memorial Drive, Dublin Road widens to provide auxiliary left turn lanes in both
northbound and southbound directions. Deer Run Drive, which provides access to the existing
residential development at the proposed site is located along Dublin Road, approximately 550
feet north of the Memorial Drive.
Memorial Drive is an east‐west roadway that runs along the south edge of the proposed Deer
Run development. Memorial Drive, to the west of Dublin Road, is a marked two‐lane roadway
with a speed limit of 35 mph. To the east of Dublin Road, Memorial Drive operates as a two‐lane
roadway, although the width of the pavement of Memorial Drive beyond the westbound
auxiliary left turn lane is 35 feet. The speed limit on Memorial Drive to the east of Dublin Road is
25 mph. At the intersection with Dublin Road, Memorial Drive widens to provide auxiliary left
turn lanes in both the eastbound and westbound directions. An access to the proposed
residential development is planned on Memorial Drive approximately 550 feet east of the
Dublin Road, aligning with existing intersection with Autumnwood Way to the south.

control for Memorial Drive. There is an existing STOP sign on Autumnwood Way at Memorial

Memorial Drive east of Autumnwood Way. The distribution of trips at the intersection of

page.text: The recent AADT data revealed that the traffic on Dublin Road in Delaware County, in the
vicinity of the proposed site, has increased at the rate of 1.5% per year between 2008 and 2010.
Recent traffic data, collected by the City of Dublin in 2006 and 2009, indicate a growth rate of
about 5% per year along the study corridor. The City of Dublin’s 2030 projections are based on a
growth rate of 3% per year. Based on conversations with City of Dublin staff, we believe that
due to the changes in economic conditions and the slow down in development in the area these
growth rate percentages are not accurate for current conditions. Based on the economic
conditions, rate of development, and the observed growth rate of 1.5% shown in the AADT data,
a 1% per year growth rate is more appropriate between now and opening day. We have also
assumed that at some time in the future economic conditions will improve and growth rates will
increase. To account for this improvement, the growth rate from opening day and the horizon
year will return to the measured 1.5%.

The intersections of Dublin Road and Memorial Drive, Memorial Drive and Autumnwood Way,
and Dublin Road and Deer Run Drive N were analyzed according to the methodologies published
in the Highway Capacity Manual, 2000 Edition. McTrans HSC+ software was utilized to conduct
the analyses, and the HCS Reports for the evaluations are included as Appendix D. This analysis
determines the Level of Service (LOS) of the intersection approaches and individual movements
and was performed for the existing traffic, background traffic without the development, for the
opening day, and horizon year. Both opening day and horizon year were then analyzed with the
development. Each scenario was analyzed with the existing roadway configuration. In the
absence of the separate heavy vehicle volume data, 2% heavy vehicles was assumed for the
purpose of the capacity calculations. Also, based on City of Dublin preferences, a peak hour
factor of 0.9 was assumed for both opening day and horizon year capacity calculations.
The LOS of an intersection is based on factors such as number and types of lanes, intersection
controls such as STOP signs or traffic signals, traffic volumes, etc. LOS is expressed as a letter
grade, in a range from A through F. In this context, ‘A’ represents the best conditions, with very
little or no average delay to vehicles. LOS ‘F’ is the worst of conditions, equated with very large
average delays and few gaps of acceptable length. The following Table 4 summarizes the range
in LOS as it relates to average vehicle delay at intersections under STOP or Yield controls.

The Ohio Manual of Uniform Traffic Control Devices (OMUTCD) defines 8 individual warrants in
order to assist in evaluating intersections for signalization. A traffic signal should not be
considered for installation unless one or more of the warrants are met. The first three warrants
are used in situations where large traffic volumes are the principal reason for signal installation.
The analysis revealed that the intersection of Dublin Road and Memorial Drive does not meet
the traffic signal warrants with existing traffic volumes. The signal warrant analysis is based on
one lane approaches on both Dublin Road and Memorial Drive and meeting 70% of the volume
criteria for each of the warrant analyzed based on the higher speed i.e. exceeding 40 mph on
Further evaluation of signal warrants indicated that the above‐mentioned intersection meets
the 4‐hour signal warrant in the year 2015 for both no‐build (without the Deer Run
development) and build (with the Deer Run development) conditions. This intersection also
meets all primary signal warrants namely 8‐hour, 4‐hour, and peak hour warrants for both no‐
build and build conditions in the year 2025. However, the unsignalized HCS analyses from this
study show relatively good LOS through the horizon year. In addition, it should be noted that
traffic projected for signal warrants should not go beyond 3 years into the future. Therefore,
the above warrant analysis represents the potential to meet a warrant, but should not be
utilized for the purposes of warranting a 2015 or 2025 traffic signal. Further analysis would
need to be conducted in the future.
Warrant 1 is the eight‐hour volume warrant. This warrant is typically used at locations where a
large number of vehicles on either major street or on minor street are the principal reason to
consider installation of a traffic signal. The OMUTCD provides minimum two‐way volumes for
the major street and one approach of the minor street.
The Minimum Vehicular Volume, Condition A, is intended for application at locations where a
large volume of intersecting traffic is the principal reason to consider installing a traffic control
signal. For this condition, for one lane approaches, the major street must exceed 350 vehicles
for 8 hours and the minor street must exceed 105 for the same 8 hours of the day.
The Interruption of Continuous Traffic, Condition B, is intended for application at locations
where Condition A is not satisfied and where the traffic volume on a major street is so heavy
that traffic on a minor intersecting street suffers excessive delay or conflict in entering or
crossing the major street. For this condition, for one lane approaches the major street must
exceed 525 vehicles for 8 hours and the minor street must exceed 53 for the same 8 hours of
Warrant 2 is the Four‐Hour Vehicular Volume Warrant. This warrant is also used in cases where
large volumes are the reason to consider signal installation. This warrant is based on the traffic
volumes for the major street and one approach of the minor street. Figures are provided for
this warrant in the OMUTCD. If the data points representing volume information for four
separate hours of a typical day fall above the applicable curve the conditions for this warrant
have been met. The points representing the four highest volume hours can be seen in Appendix
Warrant 3 is the peak hour warrant. This warrant is typically used at locations where the minor
street traffic experiences undue delay when trying to enter or cross the major street. Figures
are provided in the OMUTCD to aid in determining what conditions meet the requirements of
this warrant. If the data point representing volume information for the peak hour of a typical
day falls above the applicable curve the conditions for this warrant have been met. The points
representing the peak hour volume can be seen in Appendix E.
The intersection of Dublin Road and Memorial Drive does not meet the requirements of traffic
signal warrants for the existing traffic conditions based on the analysis considering 1‐lane
approaches at this intersection. This intersection could potentially meet warrants for
signalization for both no‐build and build conditions in 2015 and 2025. However, the HCS analysis
shows acceptable level of service at this intersection for both opening day and horizon year
traffic conditions. So while signal warrants are potentially met due to background traffic, this
development would not have any adverse effect on the operations at this intersection. We
conclude that the development traffic does not trigger the need for a traffic signal. The detailed
Signal Warrant Analysis for the intersection of Dublin Road and Memorial Drive is located in
Appendix E. Appendix E also contains the ‘Right Turn Factorization Sheets’ along with the
information on hourly distribution of the site generated traffic.
The intersection sight distance (ISD) analysis was conducted per the City of Dublin’s
Administrative Policy and Procedure for evaluating the intersection sight triangles. The
intersection sight distance was evaluated for the intersections of Dublin Road at Memorial
Drive, Memorial Drive at Deer Run Drive E, and Dublin Road at Deer Run Drive N. The required
sight distance for the left turning vehicles at the STOP‐controlled intersections based on the
design speed of the major roadway is provided in Tables 1 and 2 of the ISD Administrative
Policy. Since the left turning movement required a longer intersection sight distance than the
right turning movement, the criteria for the left turns apply to the right turning vehicles. The
intersection sight distances based on the design speed provide one side of the intersection sight
triangle measured from the center of the lane.
Based on the figures 1 and 2 of the ISD Administrative Policy, for the left turning vehicles looking
left, the other side of the sight triangle is represented by the distance between the decision
point of the vehicle and the center of the nearest through lane. For the left turning vehicles
looking right, the other side of the sight triangle is represented by the distance between the
decision point of the vehicle and the center of the nearest through lane from the driver’s right.

The capacity analyses at the intersections of Dublin Road & Memorial Drive, Memorial Drive &
Deer Run Drive E, and Dublin Road & Deer Run Drive N indicate that the proposed Deer Run
residential development does not have any adverse impact on the adjacent intersections. Based
on the results of the capacity analysis along with the analyses of the signal warrants, sight

recommended at the studied intersections at this time.
Deer Run Site Traffic Impact Study
Thank you for the opportunity to submit this memorandum of understanding for preparing a
traffic impact study for a proposed residential development on property in the northeast
quadrant of the intersection of Dublin Road and Memorial Drive. This letter represents our
understanding of the City of Dublin requirements and our corresponding scope of services.
The development is proposed to consist of a mix of single-family homes on estate sized lots and
luxury residential cluster homes. The development will likely occur in phases over a period of
time. The property has frontage to and will obtain access from Dublin Road and Memorial
Drive, which are under the jurisdiction of the City of Dublin, OH. This traffic impact study is
being prepared for your review. The impact study should consider the incremental effects of
staging phases of the development over a period of time, as well as the likely impacts at a point
10 years after build-out of the development.
In accordance with the general guidelines of the City of Dublin, the proposed study is intended
to verify the existing traffic conditions on the abutting public road system. Building on this
analysis, the study will then identify the traffic impacts attributable to the proposed development,
and, if warranted, identify alternative improvements needed to mitigate those impacts.
The study will consider the following locations:
Access point to Memorial Drive (anticipated to be opposite Autumnwood Way)
The work plan is broken down into discrete tasks. Each task is explained below.
Work will begin by obtaining all necessary information for the study from various sources, as
well as conducting additional data collection as outlined below:
1. Compile and review existing traffic counts. For this task we will collect data from all
available sources. Recent, and historic, traffic counts on Dublin Road and Memorial
Drive, and Dublin Road and Brand Road, are available from the City of Dublin.
2. Field review of study area. General geometric information in the study area, by way of
number of lanes, lane use and widths, turn storage, etc. will be reviewed and tabulated.

2. Analysis of Post-Development Conditions. Post-development (build-out) traffic
volumes will be used to conduct capacity analyses under any planned geometric
improvements. Using the capacity analysis as a tool, alternatives will be developed
considering roadway improvements and traffic control features to mitigate the impacts of
the proposed development on safety and traffic flow.
For the intersection of Dublin Road and Memorial Drive, the forecasted vehicle volumes
will be evaluated and compared to the warranting criteria for a traffic signal, as contained
in the Ohio Manual of Uniform Traffic Control Devises (OMUTCD). A letter report of our
findings will be prepared and provided to you, indicating whether this location will qualify
for a traffic signal under the various criteria.
Two of the key traffic signal warrants involve meeting minimum traffic volumes over an
extended eight-hour period of an average weekday. It may be necessary to develop a
set of development trip generation values for times of day other than peak periods.
OHM will identify two nearby comparable sites to conduct bi-directional counts for use in
estimating the time-of-day variation for the proposed development.
3. Analysis of Future Conditions. Traffic volumes developed under subtask 3.2 will be
re-evaluated to look at a horizon year 10 years past the anticipated build-out point of this
proposed development. Again using the capacity analysis as a tool, alternatives will be
developed considering roadway improvements and traffic control features to mitigate the
impacts of the proposed development on safety and traffic flow.
OHM will prepare a report that will include sections detailing the following topics: summary of
findings, description of the site and surroundings, existing zoning and land use, description of
the existing traffic conditions, trip generation, trip distribution, impacts and other issues,
proposed traffic conditions, alternatives and mitigation, responsibility and timing of
improvements. A preliminary draft of this report will be made available to you for review and
comment. After client review comments have been addressed, a final draft report will be
submitted to the City for their review and comment. After this input has been received, a final
report will be prepared to address all outstanding issues and questions.
OHM will attend, present, and discuss report findings at any necessary meetings. For the
purpose of this study, we have estimated that attendance at two meetings will be required.
Additional presentations can be made upon request.
